<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    Backlog <a href="/backlog/2155-npm-scope-naming-one-scope-per-audience-differentiate-produc/">#2155</a>:
    six npm orgs are registered for the constellation (<code>@frontier-ui</code>, <code>@frontierui</code>,
    <code>@plateauapp</code>, <code>@plateaudev</code>, <code>@plateaujs</code>, <code>@webeverything</code>).
    Before the first Frontier UI / Plateau package publishes, how should scopes map to the constellation
    (WE zero-implementation standard &rarr; Frontier UI implementation &rarr; Plateau product) so the naming
    is a cite-able rule rather than an ad-hoc call per package? The pull is a new org per product; the
    counter-principle is that an npm org is heavyweight while a package <em>name</em> already differentiates
    products.
</p>

<h3>Recommendation (to ratify in #2155)</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Canonical FUI scope = <code>@frontierui</code></strong> (no hyphen) — it is the spelling all
        14 in-tree package names already use; <code>@frontier-ui</code> stays a defensive hold that publishes
        nothing.</li>
    <li><strong>One live Plateau scope, <code>@plateaujs</code></strong> — products differentiate by package
        name (<code>@plateaujs/compliance-suite</code>, siblings); internal packages, if ever npm-published,
        ride the same scope with <code>--access restricted</code>. <code>@plateaudev</code> and
        <code>@plateauapp</code> are defensive holds; <code>@plateaudev</code> re-opens only for a genuine
        <code>@lit-labs</code>-style distinct <em>publish-policy</em> channel, never for privacy.</li>
    <li><strong>Restricted-until-an-explicit-go</strong> for impl/product scopes (<code>@frontierui/*</code>,
        <code>@plateaujs/*</code>); <strong>public + provenance for the <code>@webeverything</code> standard
        surface</strong> (already decided on #907). "Go" is a per-package-set event — the first external
        consumer who cannot reasonably hold a read token — not one launch date.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 — the ecosystems split scopes by public identity or support policy, never by privacy</h3>
<table>
    <thead><tr><th>Ecosystem</th><th>Scope shape</th><th>What the split encodes</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>@types</code> (DefinitelyTyped)</td><td>one scope, thousands of packages</td>
            <td>scope = audience/purpose, package name = product — the canonical shape</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>@angular</code> vs <code>@angular-devkit</code> / <code>@schematics</code></td>
            <td>multi-scope, all public</td>
            <td>product-line split (framework consumers vs build tooling); <code>-devkit</code> is
                <em>public</em> — "dev" does not mean internal</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>@vue</code> vs <code>@vitejs</code></td><td>scope per project</td>
            <td>a distinct public product identity earns a scope; Vue's own internals
                (<code>@vue/compiler-sfc</code>) stay in the consumer scope</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>@lit</code> vs <code>@lit-labs</code></td><td>scope per support policy</td>
            <td>stability channel; graduation = deliberate republish under <code>@lit</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>@web</code> (Modern Web), <code>@open-wc</code></td><td>one scope, many tools</td>
            <td>one umbrella scope; products by name (<code>@web/dev-server</code>,
                <code>@web/test-runner</code>)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>@astrojs</code></td><td>unscoped flagship + one integrations scope</td>
            <td>the scope is the project's extension namespace</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>@shoelace-style</code> &rarr; Web Awesome</td><td>forced scope migration</td>
            <td>the lock-in evidence: a brand rename froze the old scope and forced a full republish +
                prefix migration (<code>sl-</code> &rarr; <code>wa-</code>)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>
    No surveyed ecosystem holds a separate scope for private/internal packages — companies keep restricted
    packages inside the public org, because npm access control is <strong>per package, not per scope</strong>.
    A second scope is earned by (i) a distinct public product identity, (ii) a support/stability policy
    channel, or (iii) a public tooling product-line.
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 — npm mechanics: scopes are near-permanent, access posture is asymmetric</h3>
<ul>
    <li>A scope <em>is</em> an org (or user) name; holding the org is the only squatting defense. All six
        constellation orgs were probed (registry org endpoint, 2026-07-02) and exist with zero packages;
        confirming <em>ownership</em> authoritatively requires the human's npm account.</li>
    <li><a href="https://docs.npmjs.com/renaming-an-organization">npm has no scope rename</a> — the official
        path is "create a new org, republish every package, ask support to unpublish the old". A scope choice
        is effectively permanent once anything depends on it.</li>
    <li><code>--access restricted &rarr; public</code> is a one-flag flip; public &rarr; unpublished is fenced
        by npm's unpublish policy. The reversible posture is the safe pre-launch default.</li>
    <li>Provenance requires a public package; restricted packages need the org's paid plan and distribute
        read tokens to every consumer/CI.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Finding 3 — in-repo reality: the names are already chosen by the code</h3>
<p>
    WE publishes four <code>@webeverything/*</code> standard artifacts (contracts, capability-manifest,
    webcases, validation-generation) — types/data only, per the constellation-placement statute; the 11ty
    website app (<code>web-everything</code> root package) is a deployed product surface that never publishes
    to the standard scope. FUI holds 14 <code>@frontierui/*</code> packages and zero hyphenated
    <code>@frontier-ui/*</code> names. Plateau holds <em>no</em> npm-publishable package today — the app
    deploys, the IDE bridge ships to the VS Code marketplace — so the Plateau scope map is genuinely
    greenfield and the "reserve structure for real families" bias applies to <code>@plateaudev</code>.
</p>

